# 🜁 **THE SCRAPPY MODULE TEMPLATE**  
*A lightweight, flexible, Ravenforge‑flavored module blueprint for Scrappy Suite.*

This is the template you drop into any new Scrappy module so it “just works” without needing TOW’s full machinery.

It’s intentionally simple.  
It’s intentionally forgiving.  
It’s intentionally Scrappy.

---

# 🜂 1. Module Identity (Required)

Every Scrappy module needs a tiny identity object.  
Not TOW’s full identity contract — just enough to know what it is.

```
module.id = "notes"            // short, lowercase
module.name = "Notes"          // human name
module.icon = "🗒️"             // emoji or glyph
module.color = "#c7a27c"       // optional accent
```

Scrappy Suite doesn’t need:

- versioning  
- authorship  
- schema declarations  
- clearance metadata  

Just a name, an icon, and a vibe.

---

# 🜃 2. Module State (Lightweight)

Scrappy modules keep their own state.  
No DB.  
No RLS.  
No schema.  
Just a simple object.

```
module.state = {
  selected: null,
  filter: "",
  items: []
}
```

Scrappy Suite is allowed to be messy.  
State can be whatever the module needs.

---

# 🜄 3. Module Actions (Micro‑Contract)

Scrappy Suite uses a **tiny action contract** — not TOW’s full action list.

```
module.actions = {
  create: (data) => { ... },
  open: (id) => { ... },
  save: (id, data) => { ... },
  remove: (id) => { ... }
}
```

Optional actions:

```
module.actions.search
module.actions.export
module.actions.link
```

Scrappy modules don’t need:

- permission checks  
- audit logs  
- DB transactions  

Just functions.

---

# 🜅 4. Module UI Hooks

Scrappy Suite modules expose **two UI hooks**:

```
module.renderMain = (container) => { ... }
module.renderSide = (container) => { ... }   // optional
```

That’s it.

No panel architecture.  
No slide‑out contract.  
No UI constitution.

Scrappy Suite is allowed to be weird.

---

# 🜆 5. Micro Linking Protocol (MLP)

Scrappy Suite uses a **tiny** linking system:

### Deep Link Format
```
scrappy://<module>/<id>
```

### Link Resolver
```
scrappy.resolve = (link) => {
  const [moduleId, itemId] = parse(link)
  return scrappy.modules[moduleId].actions.open(itemId)
}
```

No tags.  
No clusters.  
No relationship maps.

Just “click link → open thing.”

---

# 🜇 6. Shared Data Layer (TSDL)

Scrappy Suite uses a **single shared JSON object** as its “database.”

```
scrappy.db = {
  notes: [],
  tasks: [],
  ideas: [],
  whatever: []
}
```

Modules read/write directly.

No RLS.  
No clearance.  
No redaction.  
No schema enforcement.

Scrappy Suite trusts you.

---

# 🜈 7. Message Bus (MMB)

Modules talk through a tiny event system:

```
scrappy.on("eventName", callback)
scrappy.emit("eventName", payload)
```

Examples:

```
scrappy.emit("note:created", { id: "n1" })
scrappy.emit("task:completed", { id: "t4" })
```

This replaces TOW’s DB‑mediated communication.

---

# 🜉 8. Module Registration

Every module registers itself like this:

```
scrappy.register(module)
```

Which does:

- adds it to the module list  
- wires up actions  
- wires up UI hooks  
- wires up events  

Scrappy Suite doesn’t need:

- module discovery  
- module permissions  
- module governance  

Just “plug it in and go.”

---

# 🜊 9. Full Scrappy Module Template (Copy/Paste Ready)

Here’s the complete template:

```
const module = {
  id: "notes",
  name: "Notes",
  icon: "🗒️",
  color: "#c7a27c",

  state: {
    selected: null,
    filter: "",
    items: []
  },

  actions: {
    create(data) {
      const id = "note-" + Date.now().toString(36)
      scrappy.db.notes.push({ id, ...data })
      scrappy.emit("notes:created", { id })
      return id
    },

    open(id) {
      module.state.selected = id
      scrappy.emit("notes:opened", { id })
    },

    save(id, data) {
      const item = scrappy.db.notes.find(n => n.id === id)
      Object.assign(item, data)
      scrappy.emit("notes:saved", { id })
    },

    remove(id) {
      scrappy.db.notes = scrappy.db.notes.filter(n => n.id !== id)
      scrappy.emit("notes:removed", { id })
    }
  },

  renderMain(container) {
    container.innerHTML = "<h1>Notes</h1>"
  },

  renderSide(container) {
    container.innerHTML = "<p>Details here</p>"
  }
}

scrappy.register(module)
```

This is the **Scrappy Suite Module Blueprint**.  
Every module you build from here will behave consistently without needing TOW’s heavy machinery.

